Here's what happens when the Federal Reserve increases the interest rate
The interest rate will increase and the bull market (growing market) will shrink, the profitability of bonds will increase and the economy will enter the recession.
That's what we know.
What we don't know is how long it will happen and how long it will take.
In the economy, history offers few clues about time frame..
After the first increase in interest rates, the recession occurred in only 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The aggressiveness of the Federal Reserve to increase interest rates is often, although not always, a determining factor in how economy and financial assets respond.
For this reason, US central bank officials have stressed so strongly that investors should not focus on the time when interest rates begin to rise but on the trajectory of normalisation time.
Indeed, in the game are multiple variables.
However, in the end, market players could find that all the turmoil related to the growth of the interest rate has been overstated.
"The first increase in the interest rate decided by Fed after the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some voices as a sign of the "cheap banks" era," said Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, in a note addressed to customers.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to normal levels but still small to constitute the seismic shock that all seem to be afraid of.
But it cannot be said that there will be no effects.
Here is how some sectors of the economy could react, based on historical trends:
In view of the situation that the market has faced in recent months, the anticipation of the growth of the interest rate may temporarily undermine things.
But at the time of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
"It seems that there is a tendency that the profitability of capital will stagnate for 12-24 months after the first growth, which may reflect the gap in monetary policy again," analysts Deutsche Bank said in a recent study on what will happen after the Fed increases.
More precisely, in the last 35 years, the market has risen sharply - about 14 percent - towards the growth of the interest rate, quite invariable over the period 250 days after (average climb of 2.6 percent) after which it returns to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the last six cycles of 14.4%, according to a recent analysis published on Barron by the head of the Nuveen Asset Management.
Deutsche said that the impact on shares tends to become pronounced later in the growth cycle of the interest rate and the benefits begin to decline.
The recession is a reality of economic life but the growth of the interest rate often contributes to it.
In the present situation, Fed faces conditions that have not existed before and that could accelerate a recession.
Specifically, the gross domestic product will approach its historical minimum point for an increase in the Fed interest rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate increases since 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was less than 4.5%.
Although in the second quarter of 2015 the value was 3.6%, few are expected to persist, the third quarter reaching only 1.5%, according to Atlanta Fed.
Increasing interest rate in such a fragile economy could be risky and could raise the question "if it is different this time," Deutsche said.
The players on the market have been prepared all year round for an increase decision by the Fed, all eyes being alerted to this week's meeting of the Federal Open Market Commission, which ends Thursday.
Although many strategies and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an increase in the interest rate at this meeting, long-term transactions indicate a probability of only 25%.
"In our study since 1950, all growth cycles of the interest rate so far have been in a super profit growth cycle, GDP eclipsed the peaks before the recession very quickly after the beginning of recovery," the report said.
On the other hand, this was a strange slow recovery after the worst recession in the period under review.
The current cycle is by far the longest expected by Fed since the end of the last recession; the record had been 35 months, and it reached 74 months and continues.
Fixed income was also volatile given that the market anticipates an increase in interest rate and the pattern is somewhat similar to that of dividends.
The main difference is that the impact is faster for bonds than for shares when Fed changes policy.
In the case of bonds, the benefits seem to change direction as soon as the first growth/decrease in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the interest rate growth cycle, bond profitability decreases immediately," Deutsche said.
The Charles Schwab strategies are of the opinion that these increases in the interest rate will lead to the approximation of profitability between short-term and long-term bonds, flattening the curve.
High-efficiency bonds work better in such an environment, although "we are still careful about the strengthening of profitability," said Kathy Jones, an analyst on fixed income in Schwab.
Interestingly, Jones is of the opinion that the markets have already adapted to the expectations of Fed policy.
"In addition to the power of the dollar and the decline in inflation, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the perspective of a more rigorous monetary policy," Jones wrote.
Short-term interest rates have increased, the return curve is fairer, the spread of the average interest rate of credit has expanded and volatility has increased - all market characteristics when Fed enhances policy.
In large lines, the companies that carry out their majority activity in the United States will have to gain from the growth of the interest rate and local products will become more attractive.
Multinationals with large debts will have to suffer because the increase of the dollar will lead to the expense of their products in the global market area and their debt will be more expensive.
