Weight reduction surgery may be useful for mild obesity diabetics
The benefits of weight reduction surgery for people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes may be maintained for at least five years according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether mildly obese diabetics live longer after surgery for weight loss than those undergoing non-surgical treatments.
"It takes a lot of time to centralize mortality data," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, because she wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, called bariatric surgery, use different methods to reduce the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proved to be effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been performed on people with morbid obesity, with a body mass index (BMI) 35 or higher.
BMI, a weight measurement unit relative to height, is considered normal in the range 18.5-24.9.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate BMI by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers from Taiwan's General Hospital Min-Sheng used close data after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastric gastrectomy in manxon - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
Mean BMI in those who underwent surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 to the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received nonsurgical treatment against diabetes remained almost at the same level, i.e. 29.
Among those who had surgery, diabetes completely cured at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes has completely cured only 1% and partially only 2% of the subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol have generally been better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
Researchers have also monitored the blood level of haemoglobin A1c, which reflects the blood sugar level over time.
Researchers write that the optimal level of A1c haemoglobin is below 7%.
Following surgery, the mean haemoglobin level A1c decreased from approximately 9% to approximately 6%.
However, in the group treated by medical methods, it remained at approximately 8%.
But this improved "glycemic control" - reflected by the improved levels of A1c hemoglobin - did not reduce the mortality rate to five years, according to chief researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared with the mansoon gastrectomy group, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), recorded more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1% versus 2.1%), and presented a higher likelihood of complete remission of diabetes (46.9% compared to 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study carried out on high weight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, Blackstone says, from Arizona University, Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery presented a probability of approximately 29% less dying after 15 years compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a benefit in survival in patients undergoing surgery, Blackstone stated that it is an optimistic aspect for people with BMI below 35 interested in the procedure.
"This is the point where this work is critical because it claims that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group," she says, without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking the weight seriously then the patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
"I think we wait too long until we urge people to take this seriously," she said.
I think once they've accumulated these genetic changes that have shorted their bodies by predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it's extremely difficult to get back to normal.
