FriendsFest: The comedy series that taught us important lessons about men's friendship
The absence of similar characters in the series is evident, given that the need for men to open is now more desperate than ever, suicide rates among young men reaching the top of the last 15 years.
In 2013, suicide was the main cause of death in 20-45-year-old men in Britain, and remains three times more frequent in men than in women.
In an attempt to address the problem, the Campaign against Unhappy Life (Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM)) designated 2015 as the Year of Man, wanting to put under the sign of the cultural question that prevents men from asking for help when they need it.
The friendship lies at the centre of the struggle towards the success of this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2000 high school students with symptoms of depression concluded that if the patient is surrounded by enough of many friends “with a healthy mood”, his chances of recovery are doubled.
To the same extent, for people who are not depressed, a circle of healthy friends reduces the likelihood of mental disorders to half.
Of course, for friendship to take effect, it must first be accessible.
In this era of communication dominated by social networks, where the emphasis is placed on style rather than substance, the immediate nature of the response often has priority prior to meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a strong personality, open to fun and success, even though isolation is actually the dominant one.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the cost of intrinsic values - our inner desire for personal development and friendship - which also affect our mental health.
The billionaire inventor of a video game recently explained that money really doesn't buy happiness.
The beauty of the Friends series was that it focused on this idea.
The characters were not defined by the workplace but by their own personality, which they showed by interacting as friends.
The humor of Joey and Chandler's frequent hugs, the moments he looks at football in comfortable armchairs and Ross's passion for Rachel came from the fact that men are known to be associated with this situation, even though they often refrain from fully exploring their feelings.
As one social worker explained to me: "my role in listening to people who tend to commit suicide and depressed has shown how even the smallest interactions with friends can make a difference."
Often, people who call us are not able to talk to their friends.
The old saying to do it alone is strong, as is the feeling of being perceived as weak person if you speak openly about problems.
Friends is one of the series that comes to mind when I try to offer more mechanisms for long-term psychological adaptation.
The series highlighted the small moments of friendship between men.
As much as helps objective, external intervention, through the telephone, people arriving in moments of despair, long-term support comes from family and close friends.
Thus, if you participate in this weekend at FriendsFest organized by Comedy Central, with the complete editing of filming platforms to celebrate the event, why not invite your friends to a coffee shop in Central Perk.
Or, even better, if you see someone alone in Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know what difference your friendship could make.
